<br>
**WARNING** Again, this is one of those deals where I don't really know what I am talking about but I have read and heard some things that I am going to repeat so if I am wrong and/or a complete idiot, chalk it up to free advice being worth exactyly what you paid for it.<br>
<br>
USB is only an 8-bit connection (i.e. 8 1's or 0's being transfered at a time). A Ethernet card is (generally) a 16-bit connection (16 1's or 0's being transfered at a time).  Why get a high speed interenet connection and use USB that automatically cuts the transfer in half?<br>
<br>
In addition if you are running windows 98 and have an AMD processor there seems to be some USB problems.  There is a patch just for USB and AMD processors on microsoft's site.  Even when I patched I still had probelms that were finally fixed when I got rid of the USB network device and put in a new ethernet card.<br>
<br>
In short, USB is a crappy way to get network or internet connection. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uwolfypaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wolfypaw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ally Poster</span><br>  Posts: 614<br> <font color=#778899>(11/27/01 2:04:10 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ameritech (long)</span><hr size=1> I want to address the comments about the modem.  First, I'd agree that a USB modem is not the way to go.  Instead, a stand-alone modem that has a phone jack and a network jack is a better choice.  Just plug it into the hub, and plug all the computers into the hub, and you're all set.  (Note that you'll have to use a &quot;crossover&quot; port on the hub or a crossover cable -- for the modem.  However, the remaining devices are normal connections.)<br>
<br>
HOWEVER, remember that aDSL is still not a &quot;fast&quot; connection, it's just faster than standard modem technology.  Okay, a lot faster, but it's still not fast.  I really doubt there's a performance issue with using an USB modem, because the USB connection is still probably significantly faster than the DSL.<br>
<br>
However, it's just not a clean connection.  You've got one computer that -- if it goes down, the rest of your computers are also off the internet.  That's icky.<br>
<br>
