Being that i worked for AOL/Time Warner Cable as a router anaylist, trust me ive seen the ins and outs of the cablemodem industry. <br>
Please guys i will spare you the BS talk and give you the REAL SHMEAL HERE<br>
<br>
1&gt; there are 2 totally different sides of the house here, 1 is a division NOC, and the other is the LOCAL one. the Cablemodem infrastucture is nothing but a GIGANTIC LAN. Each house runs to a COAX line connecting all to a fiberoptic hub. this hub(NODE) then goes to what they call a HEADEND that basically connects a small surburb or potion of a city area. Me living in Orlando, theres a Winter Park headend, Casselberry, Oviedo, etc. all connecting to the local Division of Orlando. the Orlando Division is responsible for the central florida region connecting (Orlando/daytona/Cocoa/Osceola) cities.<br>
<br>
So yes its a gigantic network, and as all my netadmins know.. it requires allot of maintenance. <br>
heres some problems i can tell you off the bat.<br>
<br>
1&gt; See they originally designed the WAN Structure to have 5 fiberoptic lines per NODE (neighborhoods) three where to be used as the regular traffic, and the other 2 where the &quot;peak hours&quot; ones that where activated at peak times to alleviate traffic and bandwith. <br>
Do they overload certain nodes? YES i see it everyday. <br>
They try to jampack as many houses as they can to one NODE. Even tho they limit the amount of bandwith per modem (done on the actual router) theres only so much a line is supposed to hold. You know the saying.. &quot;Sell sell sell! !&quot; Neighboorhood grows business starts booming, EVERYONE wants Roadrunner! Now 3years later, you can forget those 2 extra &quot;peaktime&quot; lines.. those are already used and overflowed! And you think they would expand the lines because of greater business? uhmm think again. Its been a PAINSTAKE of a slow process.<br>
So when peaktimes come.. yep you know it. lag lag lag and more lag. Trust me seen it been there. Seen some go as slow as a 56k modem. <br>
<br>
<br>
2&gt; Maintenance is POOR period. Sometimes getting a tech out to an individual house is PAINFULL. they work on 3 HOUR windows per tech. theres no set appt. its a &quot;he will show within 1pm and 4pm) type deal. Do they show up on time? i can tell you for a fact 70% of them DONT. They are required to call you before show. If you DO NOT answer your phone they will NOT SHOW. So.. if you are out in the lawn gardening, in the bucket taking a dump and you miss that phone call.. guess what  &quot;NO ONE HOME, RESQUEDULE&quot;<br>
<br>
LOCAL PROBLEM -<br>
there are 2 types of techs.. the PC and the COAX technician. When you call with a problem its up the the helpdesk to determine the issue. If its a PC issue.. i will give an A+ to that side as they can get a tech out next day and the crew are very knowledgable. If its a COAX tech. *bows and pray for mercy* Coax techs will do the following. either replace a defective modem, or replace/repair the coax line. from your house to the NODE. This is where the fun starts. theres a certain Signal lvl that must reach your modem.. this lies between neg 12 to pos 5 Db. If you are off this signal.. then they will replace/repair the line, recheck the signal.. if the signal is good.. *AOL VOICE* GOODBYE. Does this fix all the issues? N O   there are other problems that can occure other than a signal issue. NODE/HUB problems, signal degredation, line overflow.. etc. Our these techs fully trained in all this? NO<br>
and why do you ask are they not fully trained? <br>
Simple.. Time Warner Cable work with a large portion of CONTRACT companies that have no real clue on how our netowork is set up, all they now is how to fix/replair/replace a line. They have NO CLUE what else lies yonder. Nor is it their business nor do they care what else lies either. &quot;Its not their job&quot; its Time Warners&quot;<br>
now.. what if it isnt a signal problem? what if its an issue above your line? (this is all too comon) if the hub/Node is bad well this is where the Contract companies imform TWC they need a MAINTENANCE Tech out there..   heres the goody goody part!<br>
<br>
MAINTENANCE - <br>
The Maintenance dept does NOT work on a set apt, they work on a priority scale from standard to severe maintenance. So actually scheduling a Maintenance take takes between 2 weeks to one month! im serious. So if theres an actual node problem affecting your neighborhood.. expect to wait that long before anyone bothers to look at it. after a maintenance teck goes out there. does his thing and goes away. if your issue is still unresovled, guess what, back to sending a regular contracted tech and start the process all over again. This problem/issue will NOT be escalated until you have had a total of 3techs or more to your house.. then it will be dropped to a Field Supervisor whereupon you will have to set up an appt with him. <br>
<br>
REGIONAL PROBLEMS<br>
Yes this really happened. here is a Headend connecting a major suburb and the genius that set it up, surprisingly put the server DIRECTLY connected to the outlet jack, no UPS no nada.. just a straight plug in. So when we had a small powersurge.. WHAM .. all the servers in the Headend got rebooted. Is this a sever issue? not really.. just a matter of sending a tech to go reset the main servers and get them online. But obviously at the time.. we didnt know the deal.. so here comes the call pouring in.. queue's fill up..  this is where my job camed in and i started seeing routers/system that are down.. ok simple enough.. phone in the Central NOC. (procedure) they need to do their own check and balances. see the fun thing is.. everything is done by contract companies. SO is it really a TWC tech ghoing to a headend? who knows? usually is a 3rd party company who set the headend up in the firstplace.. being the same idiot who probably set it up in the firstplace.<br>
<br>
welp hope this gives you a lil insight as to what one of the major Cablemodem industry is doing.. OH a lil FYI.. AOL/Earthlink are now using the TWC infrastructure to generate business as well.. sooo looks like they will be adding MORE CUSTOMERS to an already overcramped system. But who cares.. TWC is just making more money.<br>
<br>
Nope.. i thank God I no longer work for AOL/Time Warner. i am now a Database admin for the Univerity of Central Florida.<br>
